and surrogacy. Engaging with a broad set of texts, from Toni Morrison's Beloved and Octavia Butler's dystopian speculative fiction to black Marxism, histories of slavery, and legal cases involving surrogacy, Weinbaum shows how black feminist contributions from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s constitute a powerful philosophy of history-one that provides the means through which to understand how reproductive slavery haunts the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditionsxHistory. 0aHuman reproductionxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aSlaveryzAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSurrogate motherhoodzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomanismzUnited States. 0aWomen slaveszAtlantic Ocean Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478003281zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478003281423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478003281.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles